Abstract: Creates the Northwest Louisiana Railroad Commission to address blighted or
abandoned railroads and associated structures and require their removal at a specified
date.
Proposed law creates the Northwest La. Railroad Commission (commission) for the purpose
of studying and reporting findings and recommendations of any blighted or abandoned
railroad crossings and associated structures in the parishes of Bienville, Bossier, Caddo,
Claiborne, Desoto, Red River, and Webster.
Proposed law requires the commission be composed of one member appointed by the
governing authority of each parish referenced in proposed law, one member appointed by
the office of multimodal commerce, the Dept. of Transportation and Development to advise
and assign staff to assist the commission in performing its duties, and the District 5
commissioner or his designee of the La. Public Service Commission.
Proposed law requires the commission hold its first meeting not later than Jan. 1, 2027,
select a chairman from among its membership, and adopt rules of procedure, a work
schedule, and any additional measures that it deems necessary for the timely performance
of its duties. Requires the members of the commission serve without compensation, and any
vacancy in the membership be filled in the same manner as the original appointment.
Requires a majority of the members constitute a quorum for the transaction of business.
Specifies the commission will be domiciled in Shreveport, La. but may hold meetings
elsewhere in the state.
Proposed law requires the commission meet biannually or as often as the chairman of the
board convenes it, or on written request of any member.
Proposed law requires the commission's study include the following:
(1) Identify what railroads and associated structures require remediation or removal.
(2) Create a procedure for assessing and classifying the various conditions of the
railroads and associated structures pursuant to federal law.
(3) Create a procedure for providing notice to railroad companies of the inadequate
condition of their railroads.
